Nesting journals. Boiled stained and painted pages. I live for the “what if” moments. These pages started out heavily painted with acrylics and gouache, a second set had been stained with various dye sprays. The pages had been used as samples in one of my long ago online classes and had been sitting in a bin. This day began with doing a dye pot for some other paper pages and since I had everything out decided on a whim to see what would happen if I simply boiled them in plain water. The ink stained pages were the biggest surprise. All the tools I used are dedicated to art to avoid any cross contamination. The paper was all 140 weight watercolor. Finer papers would simply turn to pulp so if you want to try this be aware. Next up dye bath for journal pages using butterfly tea flowers. Over here making messes in my corner of the world.❤️❤️❤️
.

Nesting journals. More paper distressing adventures. This bundle of papers that held some plain watercolor paper and some previously rusted vintage blueprints was dropped into a pot of boiling water using the butterfly tea blossoms as a dye. I let this bundle boil for about a half hour and then let sit in the dye bath for another hour or so before laying them out to dry. I love the results. Even the blueprints turned out lovely. The color soft and whispery. In the summer I would have allowed the papers to steep in the dye bath for a couple of days for deeper color but in the winter, it’s just not an option.  Not enough sun or heat for evaporation to occur.  The adventures continue. ❤️❤️❤️

This girl. Tilly. Sunday. She went thru the day being her normal, energetic self and about around 7pm or so it was as tho someone flipped a switch. She could barely walk. Could not navigate the stairs at all, I carried her up to my room and tucked her in the bed. she slept but did not move even a tiny bit. Yesterday I called the vet first thing and she spent the day being tested and x-rayed. Her bloodwork showed normal kidney and liver function. Her red blood cell count is normal but her white cell count was in the 30s, indicating a possible infection, normal is 18s. I won’t get her X-ray results until today, the vet wants the radiologist to take a look, she did notice some issues with her spine. Right now she is curled up in a ball on the couch. She isn’t eating. She is on antibiotics and pain meds. She is not doing any better than she was yesterday and my anxiety is thru the roof. My girl is hurting and there isn’t much I can do other than try and keep her comfortable.

Update on Tilly. First. Thank you from my heart and overflowing with gratitude for the support, tender words and thoughts and prayers. It all helps me feel less alone. Took this photo a few years ago. Glam girl! My heart hurts. Tilly has an enlarged left kidney. She needs to be seen by a specialist and have an ultrasound to determine what is causing it. It could be an infection, a kidney stone that didn’t show on her X-ray, a cyst around her kidney indicating that it’s not functioning properly or worse, cancer. It also could be a combination of these. Pain meds are helping. She is eating a little, drinking water, her bathroom functions appear to be normal, she is still very unsteady on her feet. She is showing interest and interacting with us, and Lucy the cat sissy. Now I have to wait for the referral from our vet since they don’t have specialty services available. Hopefully today or tomorrow. So that is where we are at. Trying to take things one at a time but I’m a worrier, largely because of the unknowns. Uncertainty is something I very familiar with but it’s not my friend and hate that it shows up in my life suddenly and changing everything and I love my dog. Infinitely. Many years ago I lost my soulmate pup JR Jazz to sudden kidney failure. It was so hard. So painful to witness so when the vet said ‘it is a kidney’ well that triggered and unleashed a whole bucket of emotions and feelings. I’m feeling overwhelmed and trying to stay positive. Everyday, one moment at a time. Holding my breath and trying not to. 😕

Nesting journals! Good things are coming. More to be revealed soon on a couple of fronts. I want to say again how much the out pouring of tenderness, encouragement and kindness concerning Tilly’s health situation has meant to me. Your thoughts have been a balm. I truly believe it is making a difference. We see the internal medicine vet on 2/15 for the ultrasound and she is slowly looking better, eating, and has a bit more energy. She is not at 100% but is more back to herself. It is my hope that by the time we go for the ultrasound, whatever this is will have resolved itself. The antibiotics and pain meds are clearly helping. I am remaining watchful of her and am on high alert. ❤️❤️❤️ 
.

Nesting journals. Wrapped and tangled heart. This is a secret. The way in and the way through. A compass and map might be required. Walking barefoot and leaving foot prints in the grass essential. Mostly it’s about listening to the whispers that often fall into the deep places. You must listen in order to see. You must feel in order to hear. That tiny human in this photo is me. The one steadying me on the hood of a car that I don’t remember, is my sister. My oldest sister sent me this photograph shortly before she died last summer saying I might want it. There are so many emotions it kicked up at the time. Like stones skipping across the surface of a still lake, leaving ripples in their wake. I felt them just then, the ripples. The photo feels like a lie. I’m guessing I’m maybe 3 or 4 here, making her 14 or 15. She is 11 years older than me and I’m the youngest. I was the accident. The unwanted and heard that frequently throughout my childhood and even into adulthood. Funny the ordinary things that stir up the dust motes and cobwebs in a very different version of me. This is how one mends a childhood. This is the secret portal to the other side of my heart. Where I am whole. ❤️❤️❤️

Nesting journals. Remembering details from a past life. I can remember all of this but forget where my car keys are. Pull up a chair and get comfy. A true story in black and white. Summer 1979 July. Location Sundance Ranch. Gaastra Michigan Upper Peninsula. (It’s now a bible training center, according to Google) I did a flyover satellite view and found all the buildings still there) I was 19 and working as a camp counselor. It was a riding camp. Horses. Dogs. Cats. A rabbit. Lots of skunks and porcupines and an occasional black bear. These photos were taken with Kodak 110 cartridge film,black and white with a Minolta camera. My first session the morning these were taken, was a group of 4 girls, our task explore Groulx field, the adjoining land next to the camp, owned by 2 elderly brothers and were given permission to roam the property at will. It was full of wild raspberry bushes and this shed we couldn’t get access to. An endless expedition that repeated on different days. The girl on the right is Amy. I can’t recall the other girl’s name. Two stayed out of the range of my lens. The photos: shed and girls, Amy in the field, Groulx field, Highway 424 towards Pentoga park on Lake Chicagoan. I had the film processed at either the Rexall Drug or the Ben Franklin in Iron River. At the time Gaastra had just over 500 residents, a post office and a bar and one had to hitchhike to either Caspian or Iron River for retail services of any kind and  I vividly remember getting a hitch out of Caspian on the back of an open air fire truck with several fireman on hand for an arm up and being told to hang on as we made our way to Gaastra. Those were the days my friends.❤️❤️❤️

Today I received the best news. I am cancer free. When you’ve battled breast cancer once and win, you never want to go back to that battlefield. The relief I feel is beyond words! Yesterday was not so great. At 9AM while sitting on the couch Tilly collapsed into my arms and she went completely limp. I thought she was dying in my arms. Terry rushed home and we got to the ER. I didn’t think she’d recover. I thought it was goodbye. But her vitals were all good and she bounced back, however that kidney has to go, now. We no longer have a few weeks so her surgery is tomorrow. We are scrambling to figure out how to juggle this and are praying for a miracle. Tilly is fighting hard. Today she is eating and alert and holding her own so I refuse to give up on her but I can’t do it alone. To everyone who has donated already, I am in your debt and if you can help, every single dollar helps. Thank you and much love to the moon and back!❤️❤️❤️

I cannot even begin to share the amount of gratitude I have for each and everyone of you. Early this morning some very kind person topped off our total with 5000 dollar donation. Send Tilly your healing vibes and prayers as she has surgery this afternoon, she is in pre-op now. Every like, kind word, re-posts, donation and dm’s these past few days has been a lifeline. You are all angels and the best humans ever!💗💗💗💗💗😘😘😘😘

Tilly is home and resting. Pain meds on board. She is eating and drinking. The one step into the house is a challenge and she can’t do stairs at this point so I’ll be camping out in our living room so I can monitor her. She also can’t get on the couch where her cozy spot is and lifting her is not a good idea. Staples come out in two weeks. They took more biopsies from the kidney and her liver to check for cancer and we will get those results in a week. Everything looked good and healthy otherwise. I’m glad she is home and this part is over. Every single one of you has a piece of our hearts. I am forever filled with gratitude. 💗💗💗

Nesting journals. The return of gravity. Over these past 4 weeks things over here have twisted themselves off any recognizable path. A sense of weightlessness prevailed and not in a good way. I went into crisis mode. More specifically, crisis management mode. It is familiar ground for me. I prioritized every action, sad thing is, that mode leaves very little room for emotions and eventually they fail. A thread pulled thru too tight, breaks. Last night was the first time in weeks where gravity settled itself around me and too ensure that sense of security, I stitched. An act of securing. Tethering. Being held. Holding fast. Grounded. ❤️❤️❤️

I am deeply thankful for all of you on these last few precarious weeks. Every like, comment, donations, and prayers are held in my heart and always will be. When I look into Tilly’s eyes, each of you are reflected back and that is something very special indeed.❤️❤️❤️

Nesting journals. On connections. My ability  to draw connections within myself and my own self-awareness surprises me sometimes. I’ve never been afraid to figure myself out. Go deep. 

Because of that, I’m always feeling my boundaries, often hyper aware. It can be overwhelming at times because I pick up on signals around me even when I’m not trying to. 

These past few days my thought’s have circled around why I’m drawn to certain things. 

It began like this. A series of fly away thoughts. Less is more. More is more. In varying degrees. Open boundaries. 

That every element an artist, maker, creator uses, paint, inks, paper, found things, old things, cloth, thread, sticks and stones, everything and anything, has a voice, has its  own language. And instead of hearing a ruckus, cacophony of noise, we hear a conversation.

So what is made and created is really an ongoing conversation. A living, breathing thing that has insight, a word for everyone keen enough to stop and listen.

I surmise that art is a love language. Sometimes it is tough love and sometimes ‘it’s a little bit funny’ sometimes it sits quietly near and whispers. A sort of gentle holding when the conversation moves to something inward. Deeper. The place where connection happens. 

I went to bed last night following that line of thought and I’m still following it this morning.💗💗💗 
.

Nesting journals. Book stack Saturday. I don’t know if this is even a thing, whatever. I was inspired a few days ago by @corrinegilman when she shared her book stack so over time I will share my book collections. I’ve always been a voracious reader. I was 6 when I got my first library card. We had a half dozen different libraries within walking distance of the house I grew up in. I remember my mom walking me the 9 blocks to the nearest one and after that I could go by myself. As a child I had a keen instinct for direction and I’d navigate by landmarks.  3 blocks up 17th av. Turn left on 4th by my school. 4 blocks on 4th to the Rexall drugs, turn right on 13th. This was the 3 block stretch where I had to cross the busiest street back then, University Ave. there was a light. Red stop. Green. Go. Then 2 more blocks on 13th to 2nd. Another local drug store on one corner, St. Cyril’s Catholic Church, the neighborhood clinic and the newsprint company on the corners, the library was next door to the drugstore. I’d bring my radio flyer wagon and load it with books, which sometimes was so full, the wagon would tip over on curbs. I was relentless about the whole thing and I never lost a book. I started exploring different routes to and from the library, the adventures I had were endless. The church is still there. The print company is now home to Dangerous Man brewery. The drug store has changed identities many times and the library moved entirely into the old grain belt brewery a few blocks away and the clinic is office space I think. All for the love of books. I’m currently reading The Book of Form and Emptiness. The shelves all hold books I either reference, the art collections and the others are either read or in waiting to be read. Some I’ve read and kept because the stories they hold and what the represent to me. Enjoy the views. 
Ps. I’ve got a few books on kindle but I love real paper books. I tried using my tablet to read but I just can’t do it. True book love. I’m pretty sure my love of books is why I love to make journals. Books were my first best friends.❤️❤️❤️

Nesting journals. These quiet imperfections that I gather into something fragile, yet so strong. A web made of thoughts allowed to drift from my fingers. 

These two littles have been coming together slowly. I say that a lot here but it’s true. Here’s the thing. I spent 25 plus years doing all the things. The 90s were a whirlwind of creating and selling for 2 galleries. Our girls were babies and it allowed me to work from home and avoid the costs of daycare. Etsy and EBay were not yet a thing. My days started at 5 AM and often ended well after midnight. I made performance props for 15 years. Requests started in September and I finished up around January. The girls were young and eventually 3 to 4 evenings a week were spent at the dance studio. I submitted work that was published in 3 books, one I was invited to the project because another artist dropped out unexpectedly and I had 2 weeks to create a story, the artwork and get it out the door and shipped to meet the deadline. I was making journals and selling them when Etsy first unfurled its banner and submitted a bounty of work that made its way to the pages of many Stampington publications. I taught online classes for both Wanderlust, 21 Secrets along with two of my own. Whew! 

Over the past 5 years and with adult daughters off living their own lives, it just feels good to create without purpose. To chart a creative path with no particular destination. Last year at this time I had just finished up making journals to raise funds for our daughter’s wedding. You guys are amazing. This community is amazing. My gratitude overflows.

A year later I’ve reflected on all the paths I’ve traveled and how precious the gift of being able to drift rather than run. I don’t miss the rush and tumble of days that bled into each other. These next years of my life moving to the ebb and flow of my soul is the cartography I will follow. 
 
And lastly, truth be told I can no longer keep up with the landscape that is dominated by tech. I’m happy doing just this, tossing word crumbs, scattering cloth whispers to the wind. ❤️❤️❤️

Nesting journals. If you need gift ideas for Christmas put this book at the top of your list to give or to receive. Extraordinary Collections by Marin Montagut. Anyone who loves the books of Sibella Court will want to add this to their visual library. My intention for this book is to use it for inspiration and as a sketching reference, but just flipping thru this book offers a respite for heart and soul. That someone places these humble items and cherishes them and the history they represent warms me, grounds me. I have a deep affinity for old things, especially that which holds little value. An old suitcase, a discarded piece of paper, a bus ticket, or an old tin, the ordinary objects that at one time defined a life. I’m a little saddened by how complicated our world has become, our dependence upon tech and how it literally runs the world. One doesn’t need to own a computer or cell phone to be impacted by the internet’s control, our livelihoods are inextricably tied to it, our financial institutions dictated by it, very few services if any, operate without it. Someone decides to pull that plug, destroy that formless entity, life as we know it would crumble, so to me the honoring of old things that existed as touchstones of a life that was never touched by the internet is beautiful and a reminder that stepping back and away from the precipice that is technology is necessary. What is on these pages are loving collections of objects that are  pure of purpose. They served us in a multitude of ways, touched our lives daily and we rarely gave them a second thought. Highly recommend.❤️❤️❤️

Nesting journals. The unfolding of a nested journal. I’ve been messing with the various elements of this journal since this year began. The outer cover is the pocket of a pair of army surplus pants that once belonged Scott, now Britt’s hubby. I’ve had it for several years. I started sewing patches (gifts from art friends. That story here on my feed if you travel back to October of 22) that adorned the dress I wore at their wedding, on it with the full intention that it would become a journal. So I slow stitched. Adding bits of cloth, mostly pieces with a past life that will forever be unknown to me. 

The pocket had 2sections. Under the front flap of the pocket and its back and the back and rear piece that created the pocket; 2 separate places for pages. A few days ago I unearthed a journal I had started back before the wedding in the summer of ‘22, the girl in the 2nd photo, which was to become a journal and in the unearthing, a piece of an ancient mail bag, a recent vintage acquisition, with a hole, had fallen over the face of the girl, and I knew right then what I wanted to do. 

Well as these things go I started sewing and slinging stitches and paint, I paired the 2 pieces and that is where this story was supposed to end, the story of a tiny journal. Instead, the previously patchwork pocket revealed itself out from under the pile of cloth and as an afterthought, I placed the small journal inside the top side and buttoned it closed, but since nothing was yet bound, on a whim I sewed the small cover into the seam of the side of the pocket. And then I realized I could do the same with the underside of the pocket! A true nested journal! ❤️❤️❤️

Nesting journals. This. The the broken ordinary of my days. It is my intention to step lightly into the days of 2024, knowing full well that I am sure I will undoubtedly stumble, trip and fall into many of them. I’m taking this journal with me, my visual companion. In all of this past year the recurring theme has been to let go, stay unencumbered, keep it simple and I’ve noticed that I’m moving that direction in my art. I am going to carry this into 2024 as well. I’m not choosing a word as I’ve noticed one word rarely captures all the nuances in my life, I’d rather be open to whatever crosses my path. I’ve never done goals, nor resolution because for me, those things create a boundary of friction and static, those things work against me rather than motivate me. I live in moments. I pause a lot. Pausing, taking a breath, quiet contemplation are of more value the older I get and in a few days I will enter a milestone age of 65. I’m learning how to be this age and rearranging my inner cartography and traveling lightly. All this to say in 2024 it’s one day at a time. Wishing everyone here all the things you may hope and strive for in 2024. And gratitude to all of you you share this space with me!❤️❤️❤️

Nesting journals. The inexplicable pull of imperfection. Disintegration. Destruction. The ripped and torn. Honestly, I believe that there is a definitive magnetism in things that are seemingly falling apart. They draw me to them, like bees to the hive. There is no resistance. And when things are pristine and perfect the need to mess them up cannot be ignored. I’ve had these faux Polaroids for I don’t know how long, at least 10 years or more and they’ve offered themselves time and time again, but they never really whispered to me and felt a little soulless. Hollow and much too pretty for the down and dirty of my life. A few days ago I brewed up a handful of rooibos red tea bags and literally boiled the images, along with some plain paper scraps until they started falling apart. The process of infusing age on things that have yet to have a life, other than on a shelf or in a drawer is irresistible. The point is, if I didn’t ruin them, they’d sit around for another 10 years being soulless and lacking any kind of life. The possibilities held in what is ruined, and no longer worthy in the eyes of most, is vastly more interesting to an artist, maker, or creative!❤️❤️❤️
